      "solution": "#include <iostream>\n#include <string>\n#include <algorithm>\n\nbool is_palindrome(const std::string& s) {\n    std::string rev = s;\n    std::reverse(rev.begin(), rev.end());\n    return s == rev;\n}\n\nint main() {\n    long long N;\n    std::cin >> N;\n\n    int steps = 0;\n    const int limit = 30;\n    while (!is_palindrome(std::to_string(N)) && steps < limit)\n    {\n        std::string rev_str = std::to_string(N);\n        std::reverse(rev_str.begin(), rev_str.end());\n        long long R = std::stoll(rev_str);\n        N += R;\n        steps++;\n    }\n    if (is_palindrome(std::to_string(N)))\n        std::cout << N << \" \" << steps << std::endl;\n    else\n        std::cout << \"Step limit reached\" << std::endl;\n}\n",
      "statement": "Given a positive integer [[N]], perform the following operation repeatedly:\n\n1. Reverse the digits of [[N]] to get [[R]].\n\n2. Add [[N]] + [[R]] to get a new number.\n\n3. Replace [[N]] with this new number and repeat the process until [[N]] becomes a <<palindrome>>(a number that reads the same forwards and backwards) or until the <<step limit>> is reached.\n\n<<Step limit>>: 30 steps.\n\n<<Role>>: The step limit ensures the program does not run indefinitely for numbers that may never produce a palindrome within reasonable iterations. If the palindrome is not reached within 30 steps, the program should stop and print a specific message.",
